{"title_page": "Kosmos 186 and Kosmos 188", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox spaceflight\n| name               = Kosmos 186\n| mission_type       = Uncrewed spacecraft\n| operator           = [[OKB-1]]\n| COSPAR_ID          = 1967-105A\n| SATCAT             = 03014\n| mission_duration   = 4 days\n\n| spacecraft         = [[Soyuz (spacecraft)|Soyuz]]\n| spacecraft_type    = [[Soyuz 7K-OK]]\n| manufacturer       = [[OKB-1]]\n| launch_mass        = 6000 kg <ref name=\"Cosmos\"/>\n\n| launch_date        = 27 October 1967, 09:29:59 GMT\n| launch_rocket      = [[Soyuz (rocket)|Soyuz 11A511 s/n U15000-05]]\n| launch_site        = [[Baikonur Cosmodrome|Baikonur]], [[Baikonur Cosmodrome|Site 31]]\n| launch_contractor  = [[OKB-1]]\n\n| decay_date         = 31 October 1967\n\n| orbit_epoch        = 27 October 1967\n| orbit_reference    = [[Geocentric orbit|Geocentric]] <ref name=\"Trajectory\"/>\n| orbit_regime       = [[Low Earth orbit|Low Earth]]\n| orbit_periapsis    = 172 km\n| orbit_apoapsis     = 212 km\n| orbit_inclination  = 51.7\u00b0\n| orbit_period       = 88.7 minutes\n| apsis              = gee\n}}\n\n{{Infobox spaceflight\n| name               = Kosmos 188\n| mission_type       = Uncrewed spacecraft\n| operator           = [[OKB-1]]\n| COSPAR_ID          = 1967-107A\n| SATCAT             = 03020\n| mission_duration   = 3 days\n\n| spacecraft         = [[Soyuz (spacecraft)|Soyuz]]\n| spacecraft_type    = [[Soyuz 7K-OK]]\n| manufacturer       = [[OKB-1]]\n| launch_mass        = 6000 kg <ref name=\"Cosmos\"/>\n\n| launch_date        = 30 October 1967, 08:12:41 GMT\n| launch_rocket      = [[Soyuz (rocket)|Soyuz 11A511 s/n N15000-07]]\n| launch_site        = [[Baikonur Cosmodrome|Baikonur]], [[Baikonur Cosmodrome|Site 1]]\n| launch_contractor  = [[OKB-1]]\n\n| decay_date         = 2 November 1967\n\n| orbit_epoch        = 30 October 1967\n| orbit_reference    = [[Geocentric orbit|Geocentric]] <ref name=\"Trajectory\"/>\n| orbit_regime       = [[Low Earth orbit|Low Earth]]\n| orbit_periapsis    = 180 km\n| orbit_apoapsis     = 247 km\n| orbit_inclination  = 51.7\u00b0\n| orbit_period       = 89.0 minutes\n| apsis              = gee\n}}\n\n[[Image:The Soviet Union 1968 CPA 3619 stamp (Linked Satellites, Kosmos 186 and Kosmos 188, and Space Rendezvous Schema).jpg|thumb|200px|left|The first automatic docking in space. [[Soviet Union]] stamp, 1968.]]\n\n'''Kosmos 186''' ({{lang-ru|\u041a\u043e\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0441-186}} meaning ''Cosmos 186'') and '''Kosmos 188''' ({{lang-ru|\u041a\u043e\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0441-188}} meaning ''Cosmos 188'') were two unmanned Soviet Union spacecraft that incorporated a [[Soyuz programme]] descent module for landing scientific instruments and test objects.<ref>[http://www.russianspaceweb.com/soyuz-7k-ok-kosmos-186-188.html russianspaceweb.com kosmos-186-188]</ref>\n\n==Mission==\nThe two Soviet spacecraft made the first fully automated [[space docking]] in the history of [[space exploration]] on 30 October 1967. Mutual search, approach, mooring, and docking were automatically performed by the IGLA-system onboard Kosmos 186. After 3.5 hours of joint flight, the satellites parted on a command sent from the Earth and continued to orbit separately. Officially, both made a soft landing in a predetermined region of the Soviet Union - Kosmos 186 on 31 October 1967 and Kosmos 188 on 2 November 1967. According to Boris Chertok \"one of the vehicles was destroyed by the emergency destruction system\" (See B.Chertok, Rockets and People, Vol.IV, Chapter 8, page 156).\n\nBecause of the lethal outcome of both the [[Soyuz 1]] and the US [[Apollo 1]] missions earlier that year it was decided to proceed with unmanned flights first. But because the Soviet Union had no ground stations outside its own territory, this meant the docking had to be done fully automated. After the first attempt failed (a fly-by at a distance of 900 m), the second attempt succeeded over the South Atlantic. However, this docking was not entirely successful either \u2014 the modules were mechanically docked, but not electrically. Also, the manoeuvre had cost more fuel than anticipated.<ref>[http://www.svengrahn.pp.se/trackind/K186188/K186188.html - Radio observations of Kosmos-186/188 - the first automatic docking, Sven Grahn]</ref>\n\nThis mission proved it possible to launch smaller parts and assemble them in space, thus eliminating the need for exceedingly large rockets for larger undertakings like a [[space station]].<ref>[https://www.nasa.gov/feature/50-years-ago-the-first-automatic-docking-in-space NASA 50 Years Ago: The First Automatic Docking in Space, 19 October 2017]</ref>\n\n== External links ==\n{{Portal|Spaceflight}}\n\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VIwx4CykXMM yourtube Kosmos 186 and Kosmos 188]\n* [https://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/nmc/spacecraft/display.action?id=1967-105A Text comes from NASA NSSDC Master Catalog]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Soyuz}}\n{{Orbital launches in 1967}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kosmos 0186 And Kosmos 0188}}\n\n[[Category:Soyuz uncrewed test flights]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched in 1967]]\n[[Category:1967 in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Kosmos satellites]]\n\n{{USSR-spacecraft-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox spaceflight\n| name               = Kosmos 186\n| mission_type       = Uncrewed spacecraft\n| operator           = [[OKB-1]]\n| COSPAR_ID          = 1967-105A\n| SATCAT             = 03014\n| mission_duration   = 4 days\n\n| spacecraft         = [[Soyuz (spacecraft)|Soyuz]]\n| spacecraft_type    = [[Soyuz 7K-OK]]\n| manufacturer       = [[OKB-1]]\n| launch_mass        = 6000 kg <ref name=\"Cosmos\"/>\n\n| launch_date        = 27 October 1967, 09:29:59 GMT\n| launch_rocket      = [[Soyuz (rocket)|Soyuz 11A511 s/n U15000-05]]\n| launch_site        = [[Baikonur Cosmodrome|Baikonur]], [[Baikonur Cosmodrome|Site 31]]\n| launch_contractor  = [[OKB-1]]\n\n| decay_date         = 31 October 1967\n\n| orbit_epoch        = 27 October 1967\n| orbit_reference    = [[Geocentric orbit|Geocentric]] <ref name=\"Trajectory\"/>\n| orbit_regime       = [[Low Earth orbit|Low Earth]]\n| orbit_periapsis    = 172 km\n| orbit_apoapsis     = 212 km\n| orbit_inclination  = 51.7\u00b0\n| orbit_period       = 88.7 minutes\n| apsis              = gee\n}}\n\n{{Infobox spaceflight\n| name               = Kosmos 188\n| mission_type       = Uncrewed spacecraft\n| operator           = [[OKB-1]]\n| COSPAR_ID          = 1967-107A\n| SATCAT             = 03020\n| mission_duration   = 3 days\n\n| spacecraft         = [[Soyuz (spacecraft)|Soyuz]]\n| spacecraft_type    = [[Soyuz 7K-OK]]\n| manufacturer       = [[OKB-1]]\n| launch_mass        = 6000 kg <ref name=\"Cosmos\"/>\n\n| launch_date        = 30 October 1967, 08:12:41 GMT\n| launch_rocket      = [[Soyuz (rocket)|Soyuz 11A511 s/n N15000-07]]\n| launch_site        = [[Baikonur Cosmodrome|Baikonur]], [[Baikonur Cosmodrome|Site 1]]\n| launch_contractor  = [[OKB-1]]\n\n| decay_date         = 2 November 1967\n\n| orbit_epoch        = 30 October 1967\n| orbit_reference    = [[Geocentric orbit|Geocentric]] <ref name=\"Trajectory\"/>\n| orbit_regime       = [[Low Earth orbit|Low Earth]]\n| orbit_periapsis    = 180 km\n| orbit_apoapsis     = 247 km\n| orbit_inclination  = 51.7\u00b0\n| orbit_period       = 89.0 minutes\n| apsis              = gee\n}}\n\n[[Image:The Soviet Union 1968 CPA 3619 stamp (Linked Satellites, Kosmos 186 and Kosmos 188, and Space Rendezvous Schema).jpg|thumb|200px|left|The first automatic docking in space. [[Soviet Union]] stamp, 1968.]]\n\n'''Kosmos 186''' ({{lang-ru|\u041a\u043e\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0441-186}} meaning ''Cosmos 186'') and '''Kosmos 188''' ({{lang-ru|\u041a\u043e\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0441-188}} meaning ''Cosmos 188'') were two unmanned Soviet Union spacecraft that incorporated a [[Soyuz programme]] descent module for landing scientific instruments and test objects.<ref>[http://www.russianspaceweb.com/soyuz-7k-ok-kosmos-186-188.html russianspaceweb.com kosmos-186-188]</ref>\n\n==Mission==\nThe two Soviet spacecraft made the first fully automated [[space docking]] in the history of [[space exploration]] on 30 October 1967. Mutual search, approach, mooring, and docking were automatically performed by the IGLA-system onboard Kosmos 186. After 3.5 hours of joint flight, the satellites parted on a command sent from the Earth and continued to orbit separately. Officially, both made a soft landing in a predetermined region of the Soviet Union - Kosmos 186 on 31 October 1967 and Kosmos 188 on 2 November 1967. According to Boris Chertok \"one of the vehicles was destroyed by the emergency destruction system\" (See B.Chertok, Rockets and People, Vol.IV, Chapter 8, page 156).\n\nBecause of the lethal outcome of both the [[Soyuz 1]] and the US [[Apollo 1]] missions earlier that year it was decided to proceed with unmanned flights first. But because the Soviet Union had no ground stations outside its own territory, this meant the docking had to be done fully automated. After the first attempt failed (a fly-by at a distance of 900 m), the second attempt succeeded over the South Atlantic. However, this docking was not entirely successful either \u2014 the modules were mechanically docked, but not electrically. Also, the manoeuvre had cost more fuel than anticipated.<ref>[http://www.svengrahn.pp.se/trackind/K186188/K186188.html - Radio observations of Kosmos-186/188 - the first automatic docking, Sven Grahn]</ref>\n\nThis mission proved it possible to launch smaller parts and assemble them in space, thus eliminating the need for exceedingly large rockets for larger undertakings like a [[space station]].<ref>[https://www.nasa.gov/feature/50-years-ago-the-first-automatic-docking-in-space NASA 50 Years Ago: The First Automatic Docking in Space, Oct. 19, 2017]</ref>\n\n== External links ==\n{{Portal|Spaceflight}}\